{"sections":[],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC20-10111-Boost-performance-and-security-with-modern-networking","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"kind":"article","sampleCodeDownload":{"kind":"sampleDownload","action":{"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/wwdc20\/10111","type":"reference","overridingTitle":"Watch Video (13 min)","isActive":true}},"abstract":[{"text":"Speed up your app and make it more nimble, private and secure with modern networking APIs. Learn about networking protocols like IPv6, HTTP\/2, TLS 1.3 and Encrypted DNS, and how incorporating these within your app and server can provide faster performance and reduce both your power consumption and thermal impact. In addition, discover how adopting the latest security protocols can help you better protect privacy within your app.","type":"text"}],"metadata":{"role":"sampleCode","roleHeading":"WWDC20","title":"Boost performance and security with modern networking","modules":[{"name":"WWDC Notes"}]},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC20"]]},"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"type":"heading","text":"Overview","level":2,"anchor":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Topics covered:"}]},{"type":"orderedList","items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Performance"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Security","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Mobility"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Privacy","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Note that the technologies discussed in this talk must be supported on both the client and the server. Client-side, if you’re using Apple APIs like "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"URLSession"},{"type":"text","text":" and "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Network.framework"},{"type":"text","text":", you will get most of this built-in."}]},{"type":"heading","text":"1. Performance","level":2,"anchor":"1-Performance"},{"type":"heading","text":"IPv6","level":3,"anchor":"IPv6"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This is the latest version of the Internet Protocol. Connections using IPv6 have lower latency.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Test that your app works on IPv6-only networks with NAT64 support because this is an App Store submission requirement. You can test this with Internet Sharing on your Mac. If you use "},{"code":"URLSession","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"code":"Network.framework","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":", your app will already have this capability."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Here are some stats:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10111-ipv6_stats","type":"image"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"An important take-away is that 20% of applications could get performance gains if their server enabled IPv6.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"HTTP\/2","level":3,"anchor":"HTTP2"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"code":"URLSession","type":"codeVoice"},{"type":"text","text":" has HTTP\/2 built-in, and it will automatically use it on the client if the server also uses HTTP\/2."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"HTTP\/2 improves load performance by multiplexing multiple requests to a server on a single connection. This means you don’t need to wait for the end of one response before launching another request.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"HTTP\/2 also provides performance improvements through connection coalescing. This is when the framework recognizes that the next request is to the same server, so it can reuse an existing connection and save setup costs."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Header compression removes extraneous bytes on requests and responses, which means there’s less data to send over the network."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To learn more about how HTTP\/2 can benefit your app, see ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/videos\/play\/wwdc2018\/714\/","type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"HTTP\/2 statistics:"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"WWDC20-10111-http2_stats","type":"image"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"2. Security","level":2,"anchor":"2-Security"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"TLS 1.3 provides faster handshakes and improved security. It is enabled by default in ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"URLSession"},{"text":" and ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Network.framework"},{"text":" starting with iOS 13.4 and macOS Mojave (as long as it’s enabled on your server).","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Stats:"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"WWDC20-10111-tls_stats","type":"image"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"3. Mobility","level":2,"anchor":"3-Mobility"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Multipath TCP allows a single TCP connection from your app to switch between networks. This way, you can reuse one connection instead of starting new ones if the network is flaky or the user is moving between service areas."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Use the "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"multipathServiceType"},{"type":"text","text":" property on "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"URLSessionConfiguration"},{"type":"text","text":" (if using "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"URLSession"},{"type":"text","text":") or "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"NWParameters"},{"type":"text","text":" (if using "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Network.framework"},{"type":"text","text":")."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Apple integrated Multipath TCP in the Music app and got these stats:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10111-tcp_stats","type":"image"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To find instructions for enabling Multipath TCP on your server, visit ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/multipath-tcp.org\/"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"4. Privacy","level":2,"anchor":"4-Privacy"},{"type":"heading","text":"Overview","level":3,"anchor":"Overview"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"iOS 14 improves privacy protections."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"System services (AirPlay, AirPrint, HomeKit, etc.) don’t give apps private information about your network.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Directly accessing any local network resources, including the use of multicast and broadcast, requires explicit user permission.","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"For more information, see ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/videos\/play\/wwdc2020\/10110\/","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"DNS Privacy","level":3,"anchor":"DNS-Privacy"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"New in iOS 14 and macOS Big Sur is support for secure DNS.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"WWDC20-10111-dns"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"For details on how to take advantage of new DNS APIs, see ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"..\/10047","isActive":true},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Looking Forward","level":3,"anchor":"Looking-Forward"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10111-encrypted_tls_handshakes","type":"image"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Also, HTTP\/3 is coming out. This is built on top of the new QUIC transport protocol, which has built-in TLS 1.3 security."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"HTTP\/3 has:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Multiplexed stream support, but with further reductions to head-of-line blocking than in HTTP\/2. This means losses of any individual requests\/responses won’t hold up other, potentially unrelated, requests."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Improved congestion control and loss recovery.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Built-in mobility so you can move from network to network without interruption."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"IETF standardization in progress.","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"iOS 14 and macOS Big Sur include an experimental preview of HTTP\/3 support. In iOS, you can enable this in Developer Settings for apps that use ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"URLSession"},{"text":". You can also enable it in Safari under “Experimental WebKit Features”.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"WWDC20-10111-experimental_http3"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In macOS Big Sur, you can also enable HTTP\/3 for apps that use "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"URLSession"},{"type":"text","text":":"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"WWDC20-10111-experimental_http3_mac","type":"image"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Apple is looking for developers to try out HTTP\/3 and file bugs!","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Written By","level":2,"anchor":"Written-By"},{"type":"row","columns":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"image","identifier":"skhillon"}]}],"size":1},{"content":[{"level":3,"text":"Sarthak Khillon","type":"heading","anchor":"Sarthak-Khillon"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/skhillon","overridingTitle":"Contributed Notes","isActive":true,"overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Contributed Notes"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"|"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/skhillon","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"|"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/in\/sarthakkhillon\/","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"|"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/x.com\/SarthakKhillon","isActive":true}],"type":"paragraph"}],"size":4}],"numberOfColumns":5},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Missing anything? Corrections? ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/wwdcnotes.com\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/contributing","type":"reference"}]},{"type":"heading","text":"Related Sessions","level":2,"anchor":"Related-Sessions"},{"style":"list","type":"links","items":["doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC20-10047-Enable-encrypted-DNS","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC20-10110-Support-local-network-privacy-in-your-app","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC19-712-Advances-in-Networking-Part-1"]},{"type":"small","inlineContent":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Legal Notice"}],"type":"strong"}]},{"type":"small","inlineContent":[{"text":"All content copyright © 2012 – 2024 Apple Inc. All rights reserv